{"id":"barefoot","term":"Barefoot","source":"Easton's Bible Dictionary (M.G. Easton, 1897)","html":"<p>To go barefoot was a sign of great distress (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Isaiah 20:2\">Isa. 20:2</a>, <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Isaiah 20:3\">3</a>, <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Isaiah 20:4\">4</a>), or of some great calamity having fallen on a person (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"2 Samuel 15:30\">2 Sam. 15:30</a>).</p>\n\u0000","refs":["Isaiah 20:2","Isaiah 20:3","Isaiah 20:4","2 Samuel 15:30"]}